The '''black-chested jay''' ('''''Cyanocorax affinis''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Corvidae]].

==Description==
Measuring {{convert|34|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, this jay is easily recognized from its distinctive facial pattern and yellow eye. The head, face, and chest are mostly black with violet-blue spots above and below the eye, as well as a violet-blue malar stripe. The underparts are white as is the tip of the tail, while the upperparts and wings are mainly dark violet-blue.<ref name=BOP/><ref name=NeoBirds/> It does not exhibit sexual dimorphism.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=García-Monroy |first1=Juan S. |last2=Morales-González |first2=Óscar E. |last3=Carvajal‑Cogollo |first3=Juan E. |date=2020-11-10 |title=New bird records for the Serranía de Las Quinchas, Colombia: inventory update and comments on distributions in an altitudinal gradient |journal=Check List |volume=16 |issue=6 |pages=1475–1518 |doi=10.15560/16.6.1475 |issn=1809-127X |doi-access=free }}</ref>

==Distribution and Habitat==
It is found in [[Colombia]], northwestern [[Venezuela]], [[Panama]] and far eastern [[Costa Rica]]. Its natural [[habitat]]s are subtropical or tropical dry [[forest]]s, subtropical or tropical moist lowland forests, and heavily degraded former forest.

Its population is stable.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Vargas-Daza |first1=Angela M. |last2=Betancurt-Grisales |first2=Juan F. |last3=Castaño-Villa |first3=Gabriel J. |last4=Fontúrbel |first4=Francisco E. |date=November 2023 |title=The importance of old secondary forests for understory birds in the tropical Andes |journal=Global Ecology and Conservation |volume=47 |article-number=e02658 |doi=10.1016/j.gecco.2023.e02658 |issn=2351-9894|doi-access=free |bibcode=2023GEcoC..4702658V }}</ref>

